			<blockquote>
			<font face=helvetica size=-1>
<font face=helvetica size=3><b>Wednesday October 4, 2000</b></font>
			<hr align=LEFT size=1 width=500 color=#000080>
<!---------------news---------------->
<Br>
<font face=helvetica size=2 color=#000080><b>Interview Wrap-Up</b> - 19:57:09</font>
<br><br><blockquote>
<li><b>Red Faction Interview</b>
<ul>
<a href=http://www.gamespy.com>GameSpy.com</a> has a new interview up <a href=http://www.gamespy.com/interviews/october00/redfaction/>with Volition's Alan Lawrance</a>, talking with him about their upcoming FPS Red Faction.  Alan talks about how the game's deformable terrain engine affects gameplay, the background of the various team members, the level editor that will ship with the game and much more.  Not to mention a few new screen shots to look at. =)
</ul>
<li><b>Kenn Hoekstra Interview</b>
<ul>
The guys over at <a href=http://www.stomped.com/published/jcal970636220_1_1.html>Stomped sit down with Kenn Hoekstra</a>, project administrator at Raven Software, to talk about Star Trek: Voyager - Elite Force.  The interview goes over many topics concerning Raven's new game as well as answering the question if Elite Force's single player game is too short:
<blockquote>
<b>Stomped</b>: Although the reviews for Elite Force have been mostly positive, many reviewers have mentioned that the single player portion of the game was short, with some saying it was too short. How do you respond to these statements?
<br><br>
<b>Hoekstra</b>: I'm not entirely sure where these statements are coming from, to be honest. Reviewers don't seem to be taking into account that Elite Force is not only a single player game, but a fully functional, rather sizeable multiplayer game as well. Every day I see another press release about an upcoming game that is multiplayer only or is dropping multiplayer in order to be single player only. And yet here is Elite Force, a 40 level single player game with multiple main characters, multiple story arcs, online capabilities for head to head play, several bot based "single player" games and a host of other multiplayer options and people are calling it short. I guess reviewers are dissecting it into two games rather than calling the whole package, single player and multiplayer, one big game.
<br><br>
From our perspective, similar comments that have been sent to us at Raven via e-mail have said, "The game was so cool, I didn't want it to end." I couldn't agree more. If you're enjoying a good game, you don't want it to end, and I think that's a big part of the argument as well.
</blockquote>
</ul>
<li><b>Warren Spector Interview</b>
<ul>
Waren Spector, the man behind the very cool game Deus Ex, was <a href=http://www.epradio.com/index056.html>interviewed</a> by the good pals of EP Radio (<a href=http://www.microsoft.com/windows/windowsmedia/en/download/default.asp>Windows Media Player</a> required).  Warren goes on to talk about how Deus Ex came into conception, advantages of licensing technology, several aspects of their design choices and much more!  The interview runs for more than half an hour, but is well worth it.
</ul>
<li><b>Anachronox Interview</b>
<ul>
<a href=http://pc.ign.com/news/25895.html>PC.IGN.COM interviewed</a> ION Storm's lead designer Tom Hall to talk about his upcoming 3D role-playing game, Anachronox.  Tom talks about the game's development progress, his vision for the game, some information about the skill system, how easy it is to modify the game, and more. Here's a snip:
<blockquote>
Latest developments: the battle system is really coming into its own (the MysTech effects look COOL!) Jake, the artists (Travis Doggett, Russ Hughes, and John Sheffield), and Will the sound guy have really made some incredible effects. The levels are now bristling with sound, the Hive assault mini-game is really fun, all the player World Skills are in Testers are laying into the game. It's really shaping up!
</blockquote>
</ul>
<li><b>Elite Force Interview</b>
<ul>
Digital Game Developer has a new <a href=http://www.digitalgamedeveloper.com/Htm/Stories/eliteforce/eliteforce.htm>interview asking Raven's Brian Pelletier and Mike Gummelt</a> about their just-released Trekkie first-person shooter, <i>Star Trek: Voyager - Elite Force</i>.  Brian and Mike go on to talk about the Quake III engine, the development of the team AI, their ICARUS scripting system and more.
</ul>
<li><b>Return to Wolfenstein Interview</b>
<ul>
Italian gaming site Nextgame.it has a <a href=http://www.nextgame.it/html/articolo.php?id=1093>interview with Jonathan Knight</a>, Activision's producer on <i>Return to Castle Wolfenstein</i>.  Jonathan goes on to talk about what they have added to the Quake III engine, how action-oriented the gameplay is and the slight possibility of a co-op multiplayer mode (which unfortunatly is unlikely).  You have your choice of <a href=http://www.nextgame.it/html/articolo.php?id=1093>English</a> or <a href=http://www.nextgame.it/html/articolo.php?id=1091>Italian</a> versions of the interview.
</ul>
<li><b>American McGee Interview</b>
<ul>
<a href=http://www.gamespy.com/>Gamespy.com</a> has a interview up with American's own ( sorry couldn't resist... ) <a href=http://www.gamespy.com/interviews/october00/alice/>American McGee </a>to talk about his upcoming third-person game that uses the Quake III engine( with the help of Ritual's little tweakage ), <i>Alice</i>.  Along the same lines <a href=http://www.ga-source.com/interviews/alice.shtml>GA-Source has interviewed Brandon James</a>, of Rogue Entertainment, talking with yet another former id Software level designer (both Brandon "KillMe" James and American "tokay" McGee, previously worked for id) about his work on <i>Alice</i>.
</ul>
<li><b>Another Elite Force Q&A</b>
<ul>
PCShooter has a brief <a href=http://pcshooter.xrgaming.net/interviews/eliteinter.html>interview with Mike Gummelt</A>, a Raven Software programmer, talking about the just-released Trekkie shooter.  The majority of the interview goes over their new ICARUS scripting system and some things about the design of Star Trek: Voyager - Elite Force.  Also check out our own Elite Force <a href=http://www.gamedesign.net/news/go_news.php3?id=1318>interview</a> with Mike Schulenberg and Jeremy Statz of Raven Software below.  
</ul>
<b><p align=right>Update by <a href="mailto:hypnos@qeradiant.com">Hypno|S|</a></p></b>
</blockquote>
<h3>Go <a href="http://www.gamedesign.net">back</a> to the main news page...</h3>
			</font>
